<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18430227-1035">
               <interp inst="t18430227-1035" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18430227"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18430227-1035" type="date" value="18430227"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18430227-1035-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1035-18430227 t18430227-1035-offence-1 t18430227-1035-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1035. <persName id="def1-1035-18430227" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1035-18430227" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1035-18430227" type="age" value="39"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1035-18430227" type="surname" value="CLARK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1035-18430227" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM CLARK</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430227-1035-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430227-1035-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430227-1035-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp> for obtaining goods by false pretences.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1116" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1116" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1116" type="surname" value="CRAWFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1116" type="given" value="FANNY"></interp>FANNY CRAWFORD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopwoman an to Victor Dumas, a ladies' French shoemaker, in Regent-street. On the 23rd of September the prisoner called at Mr. Dumas's, and asked to look at some French goods—I asked him if it was wholesale or retail—he said wholesale—I showed him some—he asked the price, and said he kept a shop in the general line at Epsom—I asked if he sold shoes before—he said yes, English, but not French; he had sold Eng<lb></lb>lish ones for some time, but, from having many inquiries, he was induced to get some—I asked him what quantity he should want—he said about 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth—I said we allowed three per cent, for ready money, or three months' credit on good reference—he referred to Mr. Hamor, of Bread-street-hill—I went to Mr. Hamor's, and saw a man named Morris—he was the person called Hamor by the prisoner—Morris said, "I am Mr. Hamor"—I said I am come to make inquiries respecting Mr. Clark of Epsom—"Oh, yes," said he, "I know Mr. Clark perfectly well"—I told him he had called on Mr. Dumas the day before, and wished to have some goods on credit; that he said he had known Mr. Hamor some time, and he would speak to his ability to pay—Morris said he had served him with goods at Epsom of the first quality, that he always paid his bills before they were due, and he was a respectable man; we could trust him with security, his customers were all noblemen and gen<lb></lb>tleman, and wanted articles of the first quality, and what he sent him was al<lb></lb>ways of the best—he said he knew he was established at Epsom, he had had the shop he was in three years, and he had supplied him with hardware and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184302270202"></xptr>
               <p>tin goods—I told this to Mr. Dumas—in the afternoon the prisoner called again—he had eighteen pairs of prunella shoes, which he said he must have that day, as he had a customer waiting—on the 24th he came with a horse and cart, and had goods to the amount of 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 35<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I said he must be very particular, or he would very soon have a stock of soiled good—he said, "I have taken precaution against that, I have a large glass case come in, that occupies the side of my shop," and he said he was about to have a smaller one—Mr. Dumas asked him for a little ready money—he said it was not convenient for him then, but he should be in town in a few days, and would bring 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—Mr. Dumas then drew a bill—the prisoner did not come again—he wrote twice.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WYLD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you ever seen him before he came to ask for the goods? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1117" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1117" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1117" type="surname" value="DUMAS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1117" type="given" value="VICTOR"></interp>VICTOR DUMAS</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep this shop—I parted with some goods to the pri<lb></lb>soner upon his representations, and the reference he had given me—I have been to Epsom—I did not find a shop belonging to Mr. Clark, with a glass in front; there was no such person—I have not been paid a farthing for the goods—he did not come to pay 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> When was it you went down to Epsom to inquire? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Some days after he called; I went alone; I went to two places: the bookseller said, "I have lived here three years; I know many persons, but I don't know any person of that name."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1118" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1118" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1118" type="surname" value="PASH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1118" type="given" value="JOSIAH ALLWORTH"></interp>JOSIAH ALLWORTH PASH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a shoemaker in the Old Kent-road—about the 21st of October the prisoner called at my house; he said he was about to open a shop at Epsom, and wanted a supply of goods to the amount of about 40<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I said I generally did business for ready money, but if he gave good references and supplied half cash I would supply him—I was referred to Mr. Hamor, of Bread-street-hill—I went, and found him at home—it seemed a respectable wholesale warehouse—there were hampers, apparently full of goods, and the counting-house appeared so full that there was hardly room for me to sit down—I told him what I came for—he said Clark was a respect<lb></lb>able man—he had known him many years, and the whole of the family, they were respectable, his relations were farmers, that his wife had some inde<lb></lb>pendency, and I might safely trust him; he would prove a good customer—on the 28th of October the prisoner came again—I parted with some goods to him, to the amount of something over 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—he paid me 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—he took them away in a cart—he was to have come again, and taken part of them—on the 4th of November he came again, and I refused to let him have more—I wrote several letters to "Clark, Epsom," and they were returned.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1119" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1119" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1119" type="surname" value="PIPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1119" type="given" value="THOMAS FOOT"></interp>THOMAS FOOT PIPER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a stay manufacturer, and live in Cheapside—on the 4th of Nov. the prisoner came to my warehouse; he said his name was Wil<lb></lb>liam Clark; he was residing at Epsom—he said he was going into business, and wanted some goods—I showed him some, and told him my terms—he referred to Thomas Hamor, Bread-street-hill—I sent my clerk there—after I had received a communication from him I saw the prisoner again, the same day—I asked if he had a lease of the premises at Epsom; he said no, he had not, he had taken the fixtures, and was going to fit it up in an expensive style—I saw him again on the 28th—he had upwards of 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of goods—he gave a bill, and that was all that I have seen of the payment—I went on the 15th of Nov., with the inspector, to Hamor's warehouse—there were several crates which appeared to be full, but we found they were stuffed with straw, and a few goods lying at top, for the purpose of show—there was a ledger and a day-book—there was an entry in the ledger dated 1821, to Jones,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184302270203"></xptr>
               <p>Lloyd, and Co.—there was the copy of a banking book, dated 1821—there was not one transaction in any of the books of recent date.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1120" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1120" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1120" type="surname" value="KNIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1120" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KNIGHT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. Piper—on the 27th of Oct. I went to No. 20, Bread-street-hill—I saw Hamor, or a person that answered to that name—the warehouse was then quite full of crates, and apparently it was a place of considerable business—I saw plenty of crockery-ware and sauce<lb></lb>pans, and other things strewed about—I said I had been sent by my em<lb></lb>ployer to inquire about a man named William Clark, that was opening a shop at Epsom—he said he knew him for some years—he gave as good an account as ever I heard, and I gave him a good character to my employer.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1121" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1121" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1121" type="surname" value="SWIFT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1121" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD SWIFT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a shoemaker, and live in Greville-street, Hatton-gar<lb></lb>den—in Nov. the prisoner came to me—he represented himself as William Clark, of Epsom—he wanted about 40<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of boots and shoes, as he was about to open a shop—I told him my terms were cash, and at last asked for a refer<lb></lb>ence; he referred me to Mr. Hamor—on the following day I saw him again, and on the 4th of Nov. I parted with the goods, to the amount of 39<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I received 14<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in cash—I gave an invoice of the goods—they were in a hamper, and at the bottom of the hamper was a paper, stating the hamper was 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. if not returned—he promised to bring 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. more on the following Tuesday morning—he did not do so—I heard of some of my goods being in the bands of Mr. Davis, but did not see them—I have never been paid.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1122" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1122" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1122" type="surname" value="SADD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1122" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM SADD</persName>
                  </hi>. I went to Bread-street-hill at the request of my master—I saw Hamor—he said he had known the prisoner some time—he was of a good character, and trustworthy.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1123" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1123" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1123" type="surname" value="CHAPMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1123" type="given" value="CHARLES JOHN"></interp>CHARLES JOHN CHAPMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of Mr. Holland, of St. John-street-road. A person named Davis, at the latter end of Oct., brought me a sample of leather clogs and French shoes—he offered them to be sold at 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a pair—they were worth more.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1124" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1124" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1124" type="surname" value="HOLLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1124" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HOLLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a shoe-manufacturer in Cheapside and St. John-street-road. About the 8th of Nov., a man who has been indicted, by the name of Davis, brought some articles to my shop—from having dealings with Mr. Swift, I recognised them as his—Davis showed me an invoice, and I recog<lb></lb>nised it as Mr. Swift's handwriting—the heading of it was cut off, but at the foot of the invoice it was stated that the hamper, if not returned, would be 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I waited on Mr. Swift—Davis took me to a place near the Jews' sy<lb></lb>nagogue, and showed me the goods—I made an appointment, and went again with Mr. Swift, but no goods were there, nor Davis neither—I went to Mr. Hamor's, and saw Horner—he said he was acting as clerk—he introduced Mr. Hamor to me as Mr. Hamor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you know Hamor? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, not previously.</p>
               <p>
